content: Nice to see you all here!
Today we will talk about the best renju player in Sweden. Who is he?
it is nice that you know so many players from other countries.
Indeed, Stefan Karlsson is undoubtedly the best player in Sweden.
finns and swedes, you know what they say :)
No other Swede can show as great results as Stefan.
As you know, he has been no.3 in World Championship
so our chinese friends should know it well
as you know, at that time Sinyov got 2nd place with 7 points,
and their coefiicients were nearly equal
only after Zhang did not win Hayakawa (from winning position),
Neverhteless, they are both great players!
Stefan got 8 dan title from that.
It is the highest in Sweden by far.
The next player has 5 or 6 dan
Furthermore, Karlsson has been the Sweden champion so many times
And he will be one of the main medal hunters in coming Tallinn International Tournament in December.
So, if you meet him, I wish you good luck in your game!
Now, lets go to our lesson part.
We begin with a check. Are you ready?
no need, I already won him in Sweden last weedend lol :)

but my brain are not so fast:(

If you play with him, and he will open the game,
what game will you show us?
seems Sweden players are all fans of d11:)
But even though you know what is coming, it doesnt make your life any easier.
Because he is good at this opening with either color
So, sometimes the opponents of Stefan try to turn away from main paths,
in order to escape from Stefan's favorite variants.
In the WC qualification, Kubo played white against Stefan.
And he chose to escape with the move 4.
The escape to d7, somewhat surprising.
is this black win or not?
maybe not 100% win, but good for b for sure
Indeed, the variant is not easy,
however, in the variant of d7 black wins much easier.
it seems like an oldaer HW
which means, black can make a real three to that line
so, if it is enough long to make that three,
then black has a win here.
then there will be a pseudo three
so, the three j2,j3,j4 will be fake three
this small difference is still unknown for many players
therefore, many top players will choose the escape ways
for example, in case of i11 opening,
and in d7 they will choose one of two solutions,
if they are sure of win,
and if not sure then 11.... where?
maybe no one sure of g7 win
indeed, g10 is a nice escapeway
thanks to sufficient space, black wins here.
And we had such homework before
with some people giving correct answers
you can go to old homeworks page later
Stefan is a player of "clean" variants
he doesnt study much about gambling style.
he simply prepared some positional escapeways for each gamblimh variant,
and didnt spend any more time for that.
So, guess where Stefan played? g7 or g10?
I remember we have studied it briefly before.
Perhaps today's game will refresh our memory about some ideas and possibilities here.
White always plays 12 here, to j5.
is it the best move for white?
how to find out what is the best move?
we have discussed the thinking procedures before
there are two flanks for black
try other moves and compare the output
is defense moves better than attack moves?
need defence one flank with tempo
indeed, actually attack and defense have no value by itself
the only important thing is the outcome
Let us try to evaluate this 12-j6 a bit.
Is here anyone who would like to try blacks?
so virag will show us sure win then
I think the term sure win is misleading sometimes...
but it is far from win now.
here its not easy for black now.
Who else would like to try black?
so, it is hard to defend after 12-j6
If black plays the most natural move
when there is a four, then there is a cut too
Therefore, it is needed that black plays 13-i6.
Perhaps there are more 13th moves possible,
And Stefan is a safe style fan,
Now, we will have safe clicking style
What are your comments about this 17th move that Stefan made?

so, I wonder if there is any special reason why Stefan didnt put h4

So, it seems the 17-h4 is fine move,
perhaps there was the psychological factor:
but maybe winning there is not easy, so Stefan didn't want to risk it
It was Kubo who was prepared for d11,
it was Kubo who played this 4th move.
It was Kubo who used this 12th move, etc.
It all went by Kubo's preparation.
So, even though 17th to h4 seems so natural,
Stefan decided to change to another 17,
he wanted a longer game with  K7?
As a player, Stefan is much stronger than Kubo,
element of surprise/change is sometimes very powerful...
and as soon as Stefan could come out of the opening stage saqfely,
he is certain to overplay Kubo sometime later soon
knowing that there are no more surprises to expect,
and the following moves were to be played 1 man against 1 man,
So, maybe weaker move in absolute outcome,
17 k7 still seems a black advantage?
because opponent is not ready to play optimal moves here
Kubo played a good move here.
with 20 safer in the short run
it is a choice. maybe not bad
create a black stone at f5, black has more choice then
Indeed, there was no need for 20-h5.
So, white made a poor move.
And what does it tell us?
It tells that 17th move idea was justified
Stefan made good choice with K7
because he considered the human factor
and knew that even choosing the poorer 17th move,
and then it is expected the series of poor responses from opponent
and overall black is even better than after 17-h4.
So you can admire Stefan for that tactics.
Now black got very safe positional advantage.
playable, but not sure about the outcome
and we will go on with the game
lets have one more check now

Now, Stefan continued with solid positional style.
Perhaps he was running out of time,
so he chose to secure the g3 field, even though it was not necessary now.
In fact, it weakened black's forces on the left side.
And I must stop to comment it:
White did not have any active material.
and if black was going to play f10 anyway
then was g3 good or not?
indeed, that g3 should be the very last move, if all attacks fail
the 32nd move create a vct threat
because e5 also supports black attack now
but maybe the time factor was already influencing the game quality at that point
where the time control is very short
anyway, white is giving black some resistance
and it all happened because of too cautious 31st move.
white has no counter attack material
and black has the e5 open support
Stefan perhaps did not play the best moves,
but he was tactically much much better than his opponent.
And so he won the game.
so what do we conclude about this 11th move?
strong variant but must be careful
has someone ever demonstrated a surewin for 11 G10?
for masters, this 11th move is as good as win
it is too time consuming to prove wins in positional style variants
avoid white occupied up side,a space move
usually, we just study main ideas
and leave the rest to the practical game
